            <article data-uuid="dbef507af6934c2a862dbf643305f7a4">
                <h3 class="eq" data-uuid="aa34abd978d84459a26907efd824455d">Essential Question</h3>
                <h3 class="eqt" data-uuid="97a10ef53eec418280de5157f86622e3">How important was slavery for the economy and
                    society of the South?</h3>
                <p data-uuid="54282acfdf0b4e4e9cc2fa9dafc10281">Slavery gradually died out in the northern
                    states after the American Revolution, and the international slave trade was
                    outlawed in 1808. Yet in the South, the demand for slave labor continued to
                    increase, fueled mainly by the cotton boom.&#160;</p>
                <p data-uuid="fcb6b7d2540441ff8b3d84acd2ab3124">As you read this module, look for evidence of how slavery
                    affected the South’s economy and society. Note the key people, decisions, circumstances, and turning points that resulted in the region’s heavily agricultural economy based on slave labor. When you are done, you will write a
                    short essay answering the Essential Question for this module.</p>
            </article>
            <section class="video-container " data-uuid="fcabe843c7dd43a7aab2e3f363a14a46">
                <article data-uuid="cd314007769f4681bb6f0d21819c1e08">
                    <h3 class="vid" data-uuid="6d40cfd5750a419da01ec11141603cc1">Growth of the Cotton Industry</h3>
                    <p class="vid" data-uuid="52ad8f5b5d7d45e4b463adf32e3022a4">Before the cotton gin was invented, picking and cleaning cotton had been extremely labor-intensive. After 1793, Eli Whitney’s machine made it possible for each worker to process fifty times more cotton than by hand. &#160;Cotton production soared, southern planters grew wealthy, and the demand for slave labor grew.</p>
